"script": "If you put the wrong blood into someone's veins, it can kill them within minutes. You see, your red blood cells wear tiny markers on their surface, and your immune system memorizes which markers are yours. So if donated blood carries the wrong ones, your antibodies swarm it instantly, clumping the foreign cells into deadly clots. And this is why a transfusion starts with careful matching, mixing tiny samples to see if they attack each other. But one type, O negative, has almost no markers at all, so nearly every body accepts it. And that is why O negative donors are called universal lifesavers.",
